25|$|Sceptics {{of fiscal}} policy {{also make the}} {{argument}} of Ricardian equivalence. They argue that an <b>increase</b> <b>in</b> <b>debt</b> {{will have to be}} paid for with future tax increases, which will cause people to reduce their consumption and save money to pay for the future tax increase. Under Ricardian equivalence, any boost in demand from fiscal policy will be offset by the increased savings rate intended to pay for future higher taxes.|$|E
